etymologies: early 18th century; earliest use found in Phillips's New World of Words. From classical Latin pastophorus (2nd century a.d.) from Hellenistic Greek παστοϕόρος (usually plural) priest in ancient Egypt of unknown function from παστός (perhaps) shrine (from πάσσειν to sprinkle + -τος, suffix forming nouns) + -ϕόρος

definitions: In ancient Egypt: a priest of an order responsible for carrying the shrines of gods in procession.
